<para id="para-00001">As noted in <link document="m00185"/> in connection with a discussion of aromaticity, a cyclic organic compound that contains atoms of two or more elements in its ring is a called a <emphasis effect="italics">heterocycle.</emphasis> Heterocyclic amines are particularly common, and many have important biological properties. Pyridoxal phosphate, a coenzyme; sildenafil (Viagra), a well-known pharmaceutical; and heme, the oxygen carrier in blood, are a few examples.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structures of 3 compounds: Pyridoxal phosphate (a coenzyme) Sildenafil (Viagra) and Heme. Pyridoxal phosphate shows a cyclohexane with alternate double bonds and a blue nitrogen cation bonded to hydrogen. The ring is bonded to a methyl group a hydroxyl group an aldehyde group and a methylene group bonded to phosphate group. Sildenafil shows benzene bonded to an ethoxide group at the top and a sulfur dioxide at the bottom. The sulfur is bonded to a blue nitrogen that is part of a cyclohexane that shows another blue nitrogen bonded to a methyl group. On the right the benzene is bonded to a cyclohexene that shows a blue nitrogen and nitrogen monohydride. The cyclohexene is double bonded to an oxygen and fused to a cyclopentene that shows two double bonds and two blue nitrogen atoms. The cyclopentene is bonded to a methyl group and a propyl group. Heme shows a central pink iron atom single bonded to two blue nitrogen atoms and dash bonded to two blue nitrogen atoms. Each nitrogen is a part of a 5-membered ring that is double bonded to a methine group that is bonded to the adjacent ring. The two bottom rings are bonded to a methyl group on one side and bonded to a chain of two methylene groups and a carboxyl group on the other side. The two top rings are bonded to a methyl group on one side and bonded to a methine group on the other side that is further double bonded to a methylene group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_001.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00002">Most heterocycles have the same chemistry as their open-chain counterparts. Lactones and acyclic esters behave similarly, lactams and acyclic amides behave similarly, and cyclic and acyclic ethers behave similarly. In certain cases, however, particularly when the ring is unsaturated, heterocycles have unique and interesting properties.</para>
<section id="sect-00001">
<title>Pyrrole and Imidazole</title>
<para id="para-00003">Pyrrole, the simplest five-membered unsaturated heterocyclic amine, is obtained commercially by treatment of furan with ammonia over an alumina catalyst at 400 °C. Furan, the oxygen-containing analog of pyrrole, is obtained by acid-catalyzed dehydration of the five-carbon sugars found in oat hulls and corncobs.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00002">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which furan reacts with blue ammonia water and Al2O3 at 400 degree C to yield pyrrole. Furan shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds; a pink oxygen is in place of C1. C2 and C3 are labeled. Pyrrole shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds; a blue nitrogen is in place of C1. C2 and C3 are labeled.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_002.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00004">Although pyrrole appears to be both an amine and a conjugated diene, its chemical properties are not consistent with either of these structural features. Unlike most other amines, pyrrole is not basic—the p<emphasis effect="italics">K</emphasis><sub>a</sub> of the pyrrolinium ion is 0.4; unlike most other conjugated dienes, pyrrole undergoes electrophilic substitution reactions rather than additions. The reason for both of these properties, as noted in <link document="m00185"/>, is that pyrrole has six <emphasis effect="italics">π</emphasis> electrons and is aromatic. Each of the four carbons contributes one <emphasis effect="italics">π</emphasis> electron, and the <emphasis effect="italics">sp</emphasis><sup>2</sup>-hybridized nitrogen contributes two more from its lone pair.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structure cartoon model and space-filling model of pyrrole. The structure shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds and a blue nitrogen bonded to a hydrogen. The cartoon model shows 4 p orbitals each with an electron (pi electron). The nitrogen shows a sp2 -hybridized orbital with a lone pair of electrons in p orbital. In space-filling model gray balls (carbons) white balls (hydrogens) and a blue ball (nitrogen) are shown.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_003.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00005">Because the nitrogen lone pair is a part of the aromatic sextet, protonation on nitrogen would destroy the aromaticity of the ring. The nitrogen atom in pyrrole is therefore less electron-rich, less basic, and less nucleophilic than the nitrogen in an aliphatic amine. By the same token, the carbon atoms of pyrrole are more electron-rich and more nucleophilic than typical double-bond carbons. The pyrrole ring is therefore reactive toward electrophiles in the same way as enamines (<link document="m00286"/>). Electrostatic potential maps show how the pyrrole nitrogen is electron-poor (less red) compared with the nitrogen in its saturated counterpart pyrrolidine, while the pyrrole carbon atoms are electron-rich (more red) compared with the carbons in 1,3-cyclopentadiene.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
<media alt="An illustration shows the electrostatic potential maps of Pyrrole Pyrrolidine and 1 3-Cyclopentadiene. The maps show gray balls (carbons) white balls (hydrogens) and blue balls (nitrogen atoms). Pyrrole shows a cyclopentane with a nitrogen monohydride. The carbons are bonded to a hydrogen each. The region around the carbons is shown in red. Pyrrolidine shows a cyclopentane with a nitrogen monohydride. The carbons are bonded to two hydrogens each. The region around the nitrogen is shown in red. 1 3-Cyclopentadiene shows a cyclopentane. A carbon is bonded to two hydrogens and the other carbons are bonded to a hydrogen each. The center of the ring is shown in yellow.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_004.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00006">The chemistry of pyrrole is similar to that of activated benzene rings. In general, however, the heterocycles are more reactive toward electrophiles than benzene rings, and low temperatures are often necessary to control the reactions. Halogenation, nitration, sulfonation, and Friedel–Crafts acylation can all be accomplished. For example:</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which pyrrole reacts with pink bromine at 0 degree C to yield 2-Bromopyrrole (92%) and HBr (pink bromine). Pyrrole shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds; a blue nitrogen is in place of C1. The nitrogen shows two electrons and is bonded to a hydrogen. 2-Bromopyrrole shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds; a blue nitrogen is in place of C1. The nitrogen shows two electrons and is bonded to a hydrogen. C2 is bonded to a pink bromine.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_005.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00007">Electrophilic substitutions normally occur at C2, the position next to the nitrogen, because reaction at this position leads to a more stable intermediate cation having three resonance forms, whereas reaction at C3 gives a less stable cation with only two resonance forms (<link target-id="fig-00006"/>).</para>
<figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00006">
<media alt="An illustration shows two electrophilic nitration reactions of pyrrole. The first reaction shows three intermediates (resonance forms) with 2-Nitropyrrole as end product. The second reaction shows two intermediates with 3-Nitropyrrole (not formed) as end product. Pyrrole shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds and a blue nitrogen bonded to hydrogen. The nitrogen shows two electrons. First reaction: The first resonance form shows C2 bonded to a hydrogen and a pink nitro group. An arrow from the C5-N bond points to N. The second resonance form shows C2 bonded to a hydrogen and a pink nitro group. C5 is a cation. An arrow from the double bond at C3 points to C4-C5 bond. The third resonance form shows C2 bonded to a hydrogen and a pink nitro group. C3 is a cation. An arrow from the C2-H bond points to C2-C3 bond. 2-Nitropyrrole is similar to pyrrole but C2 is bonded to a pink nitro group. Second reaction: The first resonance form shows C3 bonded to a hydrogen and a pink nitro group. C2 is a cation. The second resonance form shows C3 bonded to a hydrogen and a pink nitro group. The nitrogen is a cation. 3-Nitropyrrole is similar to pyrrole but C3 is bonded to a pink nitro group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_006.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption><emphasis effect="bold">Electrophilic nitration of pyrrole.</emphasis> The intermediate produced by reaction at C2 is more stable than that produced by reaction at C3.</caption>
</figure>
<para id="para-00008">Other common five-membered heterocyclic amines include imidazole and thiazole. Imidazole, a constituent of the amino acid histidine, has two nitrogens, only one of which is basic. Thiazole, the five-membered ring system on which the structure of thiamin (vitamin B<sub>1</sub>) is based, also contains a basic nitrogen that is alkylated in thiamin to form a quaternary ammonium ion.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00007">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structures of Imidazole Histidine Thiazole and Thiamin (vitamin B1). Imidazole shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds. A blue nitrogen is shown in place of C1 and C3. The carbons are labeled 1 to 5 clockwise. Each nitrogen shows two electrons. N1 is bonded to a hydrogen. Text pointing to N3 reads: pKa equal to 6.95. Histidine shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds. A blue nitrogen is shown in place of C1 and C3. Each nitrogen shows two electrons. N1 is bonded to a hydrogen. Text pointing to N3 reads: pKa equal to 6.00. C5 is bonded to a 2-carbon chain. C2 is single bonded to a carboxylate ion dash bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to a blue ammonium ion. Thiazole shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds. A blue nitrogen is shown in place of C3. A green sulfur is shown in place of C1. The carbons are labeled 1 to 5 clockwise. The nitrogen shows two electrons. Text pointing to N3 reads: pKa equal to 2.44. Thiamin shows a cyclopentane with two double bonds a sulfur and a nitrogen cation. The ring is bonded to a hydrogen and a methyl group; the ring is bonded to a methylene group bonded to a hydroxy methyl group. The nitrogen is bonded to a methylene group bonded to a cyclohexane that shows two blue nitrogens and alternate double bonds. The cyclohexane is bonded to a methyl group and blue amino group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_007.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
