<section id="sect-00005">
<title>Polycyclic Heterocycles</title>
<para id="para-00017">As we saw in <link document="m00186"/>, quinoline, isoquinoline, indole, and purine are common polycyclic heterocycles. The first three contain both a benzene ring and a heterocyclic aromatic ring, while purine contains two heterocyclic rings joined together. All four ring systems occur commonly in nature, and many compounds with these rings have pronounced physiological activity. The quinoline alkaloid quinine, for instance, is widely used as an antimalarial drug; tryptophan is a common amino acid; and the purine adenine is a constituent of nucleic acids.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00012">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structures of Quinoline Isoquinoline Indole Purine Quinine (antimalarial) Tryptophan (amino acid) and Adenine (DNA constituent). Quinoline shows a cyclohexane with two double bonds fused to a benzene. A blue nitrogen is shown in place of C1 (cyclohexane). The carbons are labeled 1 to 8 counterclockwise. Isoquinoline is similar to quinoline but the nitrogen is in place of C2. Indole shows a cyclopentane with a double bond fused to a benzene. A blue nitrogen bonded to a hydrogen is shown in place of C1 (cyclohexane). The carbons are labeled 1 to 7 counterclockwise. Purine shows a cyclohexane with two double bonds fused to a cyclopentane. A blue nitrogen is shown in place of C1 and C3 (cyclohexane) and C7 and C9 (cyclopentane). The carbons are labeled 1 to 6 clockwise in cyclohexane and 7 to 9 anticlockwise in cyclopentane. Quinine shows benzene bonded to a methoxide group and fused to a cyclohexane that shows two double bonds and a blue nitrogen. At the top the cyclohexane is bonded to a carbon wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group dash bonded to a hydrogen and single bonded to a 4-carbon chain. C1 of the chain is single bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to a nitrogen. C3 is bonded to a chain of two methylene groups and then wedge bonded to the nitrogen bonded to C2. C4 is bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to the same nitrogen bonded to C2. C4 is bonded to a methine group double bonded to a methylene group. Tryptophan shows benzene fused to a cyclopentene that shows a blue nitrogen bonded to a hydrogen. The cyclopentene is bonded to a 2-carbon chain. C2 of the chain is single bonded to carboxylate ion wedge bonded to blue ammonium group and dash bonded to hydrogen. Adenine shows a cyclohexane with two double bonds fused to a cyclopentane. A blue nitrogen is shown in place of C1 and C3 (cyclohexane) and C7 and C9 (cyclopentane). C6 is bonded to a blue amino group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_012.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00018">The chemistry of these polycyclic heterocycles is just what you might expect from a knowledge of the simpler heterocycles pyridine and pyrrole. Quinoline and isoquinoline both have basic, pyridine-like nitrogen atoms, and both undergo electrophilic substitutions. As with pyridine, both quinoline and isoquinoline are less reactive toward electrophilic substitution than benzene because of the electronegative nitrogen atom that withdraws electrons from the ring. Reaction occurs on the benzene ring rather than on the nitrogen-containing pyridine ring, and a mixture of substitution products is obtained.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00013">
<media alt="An illustration shows two reactions. In the first reaction Quinoline reacts with pink bromine and sulfuric acid to yield 5-Bromoquinoline and 8-Bromoquinoline (51:49 ratio) and HBr. Quinoline shows benzene fused to cyclohexane that shows two double bonds and a blue nitrogen. 5-Bromoquinoline is similar to the reactant but benzene is bonded to pink bromine at the top. 8-Bromoquinoline is similar to the reactant but benzene is bonded to pink bromine at the bottom. In the second reaction Isoquinoline reacts with pink nitric acid and sulfuric acid at 0 degree C to yield 5-Nitroisoquinoline and 8-Nitroisoquinoline (90:10 ratio) and pink water. Isoquinoline shows benzene fused to cyclohexane that shows two double bonds and a blue nitrogen. 5-Nitroisoquinoline is similar to the reactant but benzene is bonded to pink nitro group at the top. 8-Nitroisoquinoline is similar to the reactant but benzene is bonded to pink nitro group at the bottom.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_013.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00019">Indole has a nonbasic, pyrrole-like nitrogen and undergoes electrophilic substitution more easily than benzene. Substitution occurs at C3 of the electron-rich pyrrole ring rather than on the benzene ring.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00014">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which indole reacts with pink bromine and dioxane at 0 degree C to yield 3-Bromoindole and HBr. Indole shows benzene fused to a cyclopentene that shows blue nitrogen bonded to hydrogen. 3-Bromoindole is similar to indole but the cyclopentene is bonded to pink bromine.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_014.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00020">Purine has three basic, pyridine-like nitrogens with lone-pair electrons in <emphasis effect="italics">sp</emphasis><sup>2</sup> orbitals in the plane of the ring. The remaining purine nitrogen is nonbasic and pyrrole-like, with its lone-pair electrons as part of the aromatic <emphasis effect="italics">π</emphasis> electron system.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00015">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structure and electrostatic potential map of purine. A cyclopentene is fused to benzene. Each ring shows two nitrogen atoms (at C1 C3 C7 and C9). The map shows gray balls (carbons) white balls (hydrogens) and blue balls (nitrogen atoms).">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_24_09_015.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
